@@ -369,3 +369,128 @@
 ## Recommendation
 
 Treat this CVE as **not applicable** for Debian Bookworm ImageMagick packages. The vulnerable code pattern (`(int)` typecast on offset) is exclusive to the v7 codebase and was never present in v6. No patch is needed.
+
+# CVE-2026-30929 — False Positive on Debian Bookworm (ImageMagick 6.9.11.60)
+
+## Summary
+
+**CVE-2026-30929 is a false positive** for the ImageMagick package shipped on Debian Bookworm. The vulnerable code path described by the CVE **does not exist** in the ImageMagick 6.x codebase. Bookworm ships ImageMagick 6.x only; the vulnerability affects ImageMagick 7.x only.
+
+---
+
+## CVE Details
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|--------|
+| **CVE ID** | CVE-2026-30929 |
+| **CVSS** | 7.8 (NIST) / 7.7 (GitHub) — HIGH |
+| **CWE** | CWE-121 (Stack-based Buffer Overflow), CWE-787 (Out-of-bounds Write) |
+| **GitHub Advisory** | [GHSA-rqq8-jh93-f4vg](https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/security/advisories/GHSA-rqq8-jh93-f4vg) |
+| **Description** | Stack buffer overflow in ImageMagick’s `MagnifyImage` function. A fixed-size stack buffer is used; with certain images this buffer can be overflowed, corrupting the stack. |
+| **Fixed versions (upstream)** | 7.1.2-16 (IM7), 6.9.13-41 (IM6) |
+
+---
+
+## Target Package (Debian Bookworm)
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|--------|
+| **Package** | imagemagick |
+| **Debian version** | 8:6.9.11.60+dfsg-1.6+deb12u7 |
+| **Upstream version** | 6.9.11.60 |
+| **Codebase** | ImageMagick **6.x** (`magick/resize.c`) |
+| **Release** | bookworm (Debian 12) |
+
+---
+
+## Why This Is a False Positive (Detailed)
+
+### 1. Two Different Codebases: IM6 vs IM7
+
+ImageMagick has two major lines:
+
+- **ImageMagick 6.x** — legacy line; Debian Bookworm ships this. Source lives in `magick/` (e.g. `magick/resize.c`).
+- **ImageMagick 7.x** — modern line; different layout and types. Source lives in `MagickCore/` (e.g. `MagickCore/resize.c`).
+
+The CVE and the GitHub advisory describe a bug in the **ImageMagick 7** implementation of `MagnifyImage`. Bookworm does **not** ship IM7; it only ships IM6.
+
+### 2. The Vulnerable Pattern Exists Only in IM7
+
+In **ImageMagick 7.x** (`MagickCore/resize.c`), the vulnerable `MagnifyImage` implementation uses a **fixed-size stack buffer**:
+
+```c
+Quantum r[128];   // fixed 128 elements — can be exceeded for some images
+```
+
+When processing certain images, more than 128 elements are needed, so writes go past the end of `r[]`, causing stack corruption (CWE-121, CWE-787). Upstream fixed this in IM7 by replacing this with a correctly sized buffer (e.g. `r[magnification*magnification*MaxPixelChannels]` or `r[9*MaxPixelChannels]`).
+
+This **exact pattern does not exist** in ImageMagick 6.
+
+### 3. ImageMagick 6 Implementation Is Fundamentally Different
+
+In **ImageMagick 6.x** (`magick/resize.c`), `MagnifyImage` does **not** use a fixed-size stack buffer for result pixels. The relevant code looks like this (conceptually):
+
+```c
+PixelPacket *magick_restrict q;   // from QueueCacheViewAuthenticPixels()
+PixelPacket *magick_restrict r;
+// ...
+r = q;   // r points into the cache buffer
+// writes go through *r, r++, r+=(ptrdiff_t)(magnify_image->columns-1), etc.
+```
+
+- `q` is the pointer into the **cache** (allocated by `QueueCacheViewAuthenticPixels()` for the magnified image).
+- `r` is set to `q` and then advanced; all writes are into that cache, not into a small stack array.
+
+The only fixed-size stack array in `MagnifyImage` in IM6 is:
+
+```c
+MagickRealType intensity[9];
+```
+used in a loop `for (i=0; i < 9; i++)` with no other out-of-bounds access. So there is **no stack buffer of 128 (or similar) elements** that can be overflowed in IM6’s `MagnifyImage`.
+
+### 4. Verification in the ImageMagick 6 Source Tree
+
+In the official ImageMagick 6 repository (`ImageMagick6`), for `magick/resize.c`:
+
+- **Grep for the vulnerable pattern:**  
+  `r[128]`, `Quantum r[`, or similar → **no matches**.
+- **Actual pattern:**  
+  `PixelPacket *magick_restrict r` and `r=q` → **present**.
+
+So the **vulnerable code path described by CVE-2026-30929 is not present** in the codebase that ships on Bookworm.
+
+### 5. Why Scanners Still Flag Bookworm
+
+- CPE and CVE metadata often list “affected” versions as “ImageMagick < 6.9.13-41” (and IM7 < 7.1.2-16) **without distinguishing IM6 vs IM7**.
+- Bookworm’s package version is **6.9.11.60**, which falls in the “< 6.9.13-41” range, so scanners mark it as “vulnerable.”
+- In reality, the **bug is in the IM7 implementation**. The IM6 implementation is a different design (pointer into cache, no `r[128]`), so **the issue cannot occur** on Bookworm’s build.
+
+Hence the finding is a **false positive** for Bookworm.
+
+---
+
+## Comparison Table
+
+| Aspect | ImageMagick 7.x (vulnerable) | ImageMagick 6.x (Bookworm — not vulnerable) |
+|--------|------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|
+| **File** | `MagickCore/resize.c` | `magick/resize.c` |
+| **Buffer for result pixels** | `Quantum r[128];` (fixed stack buffer) | `PixelPacket *r;` with `r = q` (pointer into cache) |
+| **Overflow possible?** | Yes — 128 elements can be exceeded | No — no fixed 128-element stack buffer |
+| **Pixel type** | `Quantum` (IM7 channel type) | `PixelPacket` (IM6 structure) |
+
+---
+
+## Recommendation
+
+- **Treat CVE-2026-30929 as a false positive** for Debian Bookworm’s ImageMagick package (6.9.11.60).
+- **No patch or rebuild is required** for this CVE on Bookworm; the vulnerable code is not present.
+- In compliance or audit reports, you can document that the CVE applies to ImageMagick 7.x’s implementation and that Bookworm’s ImageMagick 6.x uses a different, non-vulnerable implementation.
+
+---
+
+## References
+
+- [GitHub Advisory GHSA-rqq8-jh93-f4vg](https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/security/advisories/GHSA-rqq8-jh93-f4vg) (IM7)
+- [NVD – CVE-2026-30929](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2026-30929)
+- ImageMagick 6 source: `magick/resize.c` — `MagnifyImage()` (pointer-based; no `r[128]`)
+- ImageMagick 7 fix commits (IM7 only): e.g. `adf831c`, `b09a9a6`, `bf5512c` in ImageMagick/ImageMagick
